    {
        "content": "<p>In the first case, what you write is like \"for all <code>n : Nat</code> create an inductive type <code>Even n</code>\". The idea is that the parameter <code>n</code> is outside the inductive declaration. But what you are doing in the second case is creating an inductive family (see <a href=\"https://lean-lang.org/theorem_proving_in_lean4/inductive_types.html#inductive-families\">here</a>), i.e. you define a whole family of types indexed by <code>Nat</code> inductively. So the two writing are not equivalent (whereas they kinda are in <code>theorem</code> or <code>def</code>).</p>",
